  • Use TensorFlow or PyTorch in Python

  • A small Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) works

  • Or use transfer learning:

    • MobileNet

    • ResNet

    • EfficientNet

  • Transfer learning is much easier for a beginner because you reuse a pre-trained model.

Example code (Keras, very simple):

python
from tensorflow.keras.applications import MobileNetV2
from tensorflow.keras import layers, models

# load base model
base_model = MobileNetV2(weights="imagenet", include_top=False, input_shape=(224,224,3))
base_model.trainable = False

# add custom classifier
model = models.Sequential([
    base_model,
    layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(),
    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(3, activation='softmax') # for 3 classes
])

model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

👉 Train it on your dataset.
👉 Save it as model.h5

✅ Step 3: Integrate the AI model with Flask

  • Use TensorFlow to load the saved model.h5

  • When a user uploads an image, your backend will:

    • Receive the image

    • Preprocess it (resize to 224x224, normalize pixel values)

    • Pass it to model.predict()

    • Get the predicted category

    • Store that category along with the complaint

🟢 Step 3: Write the app.py

Here is your starter code:

python
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify, render_template, send_from_directory
from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_cors import CORS
import os

app = Flask(__name__)
CORS(app)

# configure
app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite:///complaints.db'
app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'] = 'uploads'

db = SQLAlchemy(app)

# complaint model
class Complaint(db.Model):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
    description = db.Column(db.String(500))
    image_filename = db.Column(db.String(200))
    latitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    longitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    status = db.Column(db.String(50), default='pending')
    category = db.Column(db.String(50), default='unknown')

with app.app_context():
    db.create_all()

# home route
@app.route('/')
def index():
    return "Municipal Complaint System API is running."

# submit complaint
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['POST'])
def submit_complaint():
    description = request.form['description']
    latitude = request.form['latitude']
    longitude = request.form['longitude']
    image = request.files['image']

    image.save(os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename))

    complaint = Complaint(
        description=description,
        image_filename=image.filename,
        latitude=latitude,
        longitude=longitude
    )

    db.session.add(complaint)
    db.session.commit()

    return jsonify({"message": "Complaint submitted successfully."})

# list complaints
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['GET'])
def list_complaints():
    complaints = Complaint.query.all()
    result = []
    for c in complaints:
        result.append({
            'id': c.id,
            'description': c.description,
            'image': c.image_filename,
            'latitude': c.latitude,
            'longitude': c.longitude,
            'status': c.status,
            'category': c.category
        })
    return jsonify(result)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)

✅ Save that as app.py
✅ Create the uploads folder so images can be stored

✅ The issue:

ERROR: Could not find a version that satisfies the requirement tensorflow

This usually happens because:

  • your Python version is incompatible

  • your pip is outdated

  • or your environment is missing a compiler

✅ Solution step by step

1️⃣ Check your Python version

Run:

bash
python --version

TensorFlow generally needs Python 3.8, 3.9, 3.10, or 3.11
👉 If you have Python 3.12, TensorFlow does not support it yet.

⚠️ If you see Python 3.12.x, you must install Python 3.10:

✅ Download it from Python 3.10.12
✅ Install it
✅ Then set it as default by:

bash
py -3.10 -m venv myenv
myenv\Scripts\activate

and continue from there.

2️⃣ Upgrade pip

Run:

bash
python -m pip install --upgrade pip

3️⃣ Try to install TensorFlow again

After checking Python version & upgrading pip, do:

bash
pip install tensorflow

If you want a lightweight version (for easier installation), try:

bash
pip install tensorflow-cpu

✅ That works on most systems.

✅ Summary checklist:

✅ Check Python version (must be 3.8–3.11)
✅ Upgrade pip

👉 Create a new file in your project folder:

bash
municipal-complaint-system/templates/complaint_form.html

✅ Paste this code inside it:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Municipal Complaint Registration</title>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial; padding: 20px; }
    label { display: block; margin-top: 10px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Municipal Complaint Registration</h1>
  <form id="complaintForm">
    <label>Description:</label>
    <textarea name="description" id="description" required></textarea>

    <label>Photo:</label>
    <input type="file" name="image" id="image" accept="image/*" required />

    <button type="submit">Submit Complaint</button>
  </form>

  <p id="status"></p>

  <script>
    document.getElementById("complaintForm").addEventListener("submit", function(e) {
      e.preventDefault();

      if (!navigator.geolocation) {
        alert("Geolocation is not supported by your browser");
        return;
      }

      navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(function(position) {
        const latitude = position.coords.latitude;
        const longitude = position.coords.longitude;

        const formData = new FormData();
        formData.append("description", document.getElementById("description").value);
        formData.append("image", document.getElementById("image").files[0]);
        formData.append("latitude", latitude);
        formData.append("longitude", longitude);

        fetch("/api/complaints", {
          method: "POST",
          body: formData
        })
        .then(response => response.json())
        .then(data => {
          document.getElementById("status").textContent = data.message;
        })
        .catch(error => {
          console.error("Error:", error);
          document.getElementById("status").textContent = "Error submitting complaint";
        });

      }, function(error) {
        alert("Unable to get your location");
      });
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>

✅ Save that as complaint_form.html inside templates/.

🚀 1️⃣ app.py (full code)

python
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify, render_template
from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_cors import CORS
import os

app = Flask(__name__)
CORS(app)

app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite:///complaints.db'
app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'] = 'uploads'

db = SQLAlchemy(app)

class Complaint(db.Model):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
    description = db.Column(db.String(500))
    image_filename = db.Column(db.String(200))
    latitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    longitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    status = db.Column(db.String(50), default='pending')
    category = db.Column(db.String(50), default='unknown')

with app.app_context():
    db.create_all()

@app.route('/')
def index():
    return "Municipal Complaint System API is running."

@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['POST'])
def submit_complaint():
    description = request.form['description']
    latitude = request.form['latitude']
    longitude = request.form['longitude']
    image = request.files['image']
    image.save(os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename))

    complaint = Complaint(
        description=description,
        image_filename=image.filename,
        latitude=latitude,
        longitude=longitude
    )
    db.session.add(complaint)
    db.session.commit()
    return jsonify({"message": "Complaint submitted successfully."})

@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['GET'])
def list_complaints():
    complaints = Complaint.query.all()
    result = []
    for c in complaints:
        result.append({
            'id': c.id,
            'description': c.description,
            'image': c.image_filename,
            'latitude': c.latitude,
            'longitude': c.longitude,
            'status': c.status,
            'category': c.category
        })
    return jsonify(result)

@app.route('/api/complaints/<int:id>/status', methods=['PUT'])
def update_status(id):
    data = request.get_json()
    complaint = Complaint.query.get(id)
    if complaint:
        complaint.status = data['status']
        db.session.commit()
        return jsonify({"message": "Status updated successfully."})
    else:
        return jsonify({"error": "Complaint not found."}), 404

@app.route('/complaint-form')
def complaint_form():
    return render_template('complaint_form.html')

@app.route('/admin')
def admin_panel():
    return render_template('admin.html')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)

🚀 How will this work?

  • when a complaint is submitted, your Flask app will predict its category (for example: garbage, water, road, etc.)

  • it will then store that category in the database automatically

✅ Step 1: Install scikit-learn

bash
pip install scikit-learn

✅ Step 2: Add a simple model

👉 Here’s a basic text classification model you can drop into a Python file named classifier.py:

classifier.py

python
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import CountVectorizer
from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB

# some example training data
training_data = [
    ("garbage on street", "garbage"),
    ("overflowing dustbin", "garbage"),
    ("leaking water pipe", "water"),
    ("no drinking water", "water"),
    ("pothole on road", "road"),
    ("broken street light", "road"),
    ("sewage issue", "water"),
]

texts = [t[0] for t in training_data]
labels = [t[1] for t in training_data]

vectorizer = CountVectorizer()
X_train = vectorizer.fit_transform(texts)

classifier = MultinomialNB()
classifier.fit(X_train, labels)

def predict_category(text):
    X_test = vectorizer.transform([text])
    return classifier.predict(X_test)[0]

✅ Save that file in the same folder as app.py.

    longitude = request.form['longitude']
    image = request.files['image']
    image.save(os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename))

    # use AI to predict category
    category = predict_category(description)

    complaint = Complaint(
        description=description,
        image_filename=image.filename,
        latitude=latitude,
        longitude=longitude,
        category=category
    )
    db.session.add(complaint)

    return jsonify({"message": "Complaint submitted successfully."})

python
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify, render_template
from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_cors import CORS
import os
from classifier import predict_category

app = Flask(__name__)
CORS(app)

app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite:///complaints.db'
app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'] = 'uploads'

db = SQLAlchemy(app)

# Complaint model
class Complaint(db.Model):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
    description = db.Column(db.String(500))
    image_filename = db.Column(db.String(200))
    latitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    longitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    status = db.Column(db.String(50), default='pending')
    category = db.Column(db.String(50), default='unknown')

# create database
with app.app_context():
    db.create_all()

# Home route
@app.route('/')
def index():
    return "Municipal Complaint System API is running."

# submit complaint
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['POST'])
def submit_complaint():
    description = request.form['description']
    latitude = request.form['latitude']
    longitude = request.form['longitude']
    image = request.files['image']
    image.save(os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename))

    # use AI to predict category
    category = predict_category(description)

    complaint = Complaint(
        description=description,
        image_filename=image.filename,
        latitude=latitude,
        longitude=longitude,
        category=category
    )
    db.session.add(complaint)
    db.session.commit()
    return jsonify({"message": "Complaint submitted successfully."})

# get list of complaints
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['GET'])
def list_complaints():
    complaints = Complaint.query.all()
    result = []
    for c in complaints:
        result.append({
            'id': c.id,
            'description': c.description,
            'image': c.image_filename,
            'latitude': c.latitude,
            'longitude': c.longitude,
            'status': c.status,
            'category': c.category
        })
    return jsonify(result)

# update status
@app.route('/api/complaints/<int:id>/status', methods=['PUT'])
def update_status(id):
    data = request.get_json()
    complaint = Complaint.query.get(id)
    if complaint:
        complaint.status = data['status']
        db.session.commit()
        return jsonify({"message": "Status updated successfully."})
    else:
        return jsonify({"error": "Complaint not found."}), 404

# HTML form to submit a complaint
@app.route('/complaint-form')
def complaint_form():
    return render_template('complaint_form.html')

# Admin dashboard
@app.route('/admin')
def admin_dashboard():
    return render_template('admin.html')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)

@app.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])

        else:

    return '''

        </form>
    '''

python
@app.route('/admin')
def admin_dashboard():

    return render_template('admin.html')

(optional but good):

python
@app.route('/logout')
def logout():

python
app.secret_key = 'replace_this_with_a_secret'

Why you need this?

  • Flask uses session cookies to remember who is logged in

  • to keep those cookies secure, Flask encrypts them with this secret_key

✅ You MUST have a secret key if you use session.
If you don’t, Flask will throw errors like:

vbnet
RuntimeError: The session is unavailable because no secret key was set.

You can put any random string for the secret key. For example:

python
app.secret_key = 'my_super_secret_12345'

or generate one randomly:

python
import secrets
secrets.token_hex(16)

👉 then copy that random string into your app.secret_key.

Keep it simple while testing:

python
app.secret_key = 'testing123'

✅ Later, in production, you should use a long, random, secret key.

In short: do not remove that line — just set a simple string for now.
That’s required for login sessions to work in Flask.

from flask import Flask, request, jsonify, render_template, session, redirect, url_for
from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_cors import CORS
import os
from classifier import predict_category

app = Flask(__name__)
app.secret_key = 'sejal_432'  # your session secret
CORS(app)

app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite:///complaints.db'
app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'] = 'uploads'

db = SQLAlchemy(app)

# database model
class Complaint(db.Model):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
    description = db.Column(db.String(500))
    image_filename = db.Column(db.String(200))
    latitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    longitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    status = db.Column(db.String(50), default='pending')
    category = db.Column(db.String(50), default='unknown')

with app.app_context():
    db.create_all()

# Home route
@app.route('/')
def index():
    return "Municipal Complaint System API is running."

# submit complaint
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['POST'])
def submit_complaint():
    description = request.form['description']
    latitude = request.form['latitude']
    longitude = request.form['longitude']
    image = request.files['image']
    image.save(os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename))

    # AI category
    category = predict_category(description)

    complaint = Complaint(
        description=description,
        image_filename=image.filename,
        latitude=latitude,
        longitude=longitude,
        category=category
    )
    db.session.add(complaint)
    db.session.commit()
    return jsonify({"message": "Complaint submitted successfully."})

# list complaints
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['GET'])
def list_complaints():
    complaints = Complaint.query.all()
    result = []
    for c in complaints:
        result.append({
            'id': c.id,
            'description': c.description,
            'image': c.image_filename,
            'latitude': c.latitude,
            'longitude': c.longitude,
            'status': c.status,
            'category': c.category
        })
    return jsonify(result)

# update complaint status
@app.route('/api/complaints/<int:id>/status', methods=['PUT'])
def update_status(id):
    data = request.get_json()
    complaint = Complaint.query.get(id)
    if complaint:
        complaint.status = data['status']
        db.session.commit()
        return jsonify({"message": "Status updated successfully."})
    else:
        return jsonify({"error": "Complaint not found."}), 404

# complaint form route
@app.route('/complaint-form')
def complaint_form():
    return render_template('complaint_form.html')

# admin dashboard route
@app.route('/admin')
def admin_dashboard():
    if not session.get('admin_logged_in'):
        return redirect(url_for('login'))
    return render_template('admin.html')

# login route
@app.route('/login', methods=['GET', 'POST'])
def login():
    if request.method == 'POST':
        username = request.form['username']
        password = request.form['password']
        if username == 'admin' and password == 'password':
            session['admin_logged_in'] = True
            return redirect(url_for('admin_dashboard'))
        else:
            return "Invalid credentials", 401
    return '''
        <h2>Admin Login</h2>
        <form method="post">
            <input name="username" placeholder="Username"/><br>
            <input type="password" name="password" placeholder="Password"/><br>
            <button type="submit">Login</button>
        </form>
    '''

# logout route
@app.route('/logout')
def logout():
    session.pop('admin_logged_in', None)
    return redirect(url_for('login'))

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)

🚀 Gmail App Password Setup Step-by-Step

Google no longer allows normal passwords in most apps — you must create a special “App Password”.

  • sign in again if asked

    // Ask for user location
    if (navigator.geolocation) {
      navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(
        function(position) {
          document.getElementById('latitude').value = position.coords.latitude;
          document.getElementById('longitude').value = position.coords.longitude;
        },
        function(error) {
          console.error("Error getting location", error);
          alert("Location permission denied. Please enter manually.");

      alert("Geolocation is not supported by this browser.");
    }

python
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify, render_template, redirect, url_for, session
from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_cors import CORS
import os

app = Flask(__name__)
CORS(app)

app.secret_key = 'sejal_432'

app.config['SQLALCHEMY_DATABASE_URI'] = 'sqlite:///complaints.db'
app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'] = 'uploads'

db = SQLAlchemy(app)

# Complaint model
class Complaint(db.Model):
    id = db.Column(db.Integer, primary_key=True)
    description = db.Column(db.String(500))
    image_filename = db.Column(db.String(200))
    latitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    longitude = db.Column(db.Float)
    maps_url = db.Column(db.String(500))
    status = db.Column(db.String(50), default='pending')
    category = db.Column(db.String(50), default='unknown')

# initialize
with app.app_context():
    db.create_all()

# homepage
@app.route('/')
def index():
    return redirect(url_for('complaint_form'))

# complaint form page
@app.route('/complaint-form')
def complaint_form():
    return render_template('complaint_form.html')

# admin page
@app.route('/admin')
def admin():
    return render_template('admin.html')

# API submit complaint
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['POST'])
def submit_complaint():
    description = request.form['description']
    latitude = request.form['latitude']
    longitude = request.form['longitude']
    image = request.files['image']
    image.save(os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename))
    
    maps_url = f"https://maps.google.com/?q={latitude},{longitude}"

    complaint = Complaint(
        description=description,
        image_filename=image.filename,
        latitude=float(latitude),
        longitude=float(longitude),
        maps_url=maps_url
    )
    db.session.add(complaint)
    db.session.commit()
    return jsonify({"message": "Complaint submitted successfully."})

# API get complaints
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['GET'])
def list_complaints():
    complaints = Complaint.query.all()
    result = []
    for c in complaints:
        result.append({
            'id': c.id,
            'description': c.description,
            'image': c.image_filename,
            'latitude': c.latitude,
            'longitude': c.longitude,
            'status': c.status,
            'category': c.category,
            'map_url': c.maps_url
        })
    return jsonify(result)

# update status
@app.route('/api/complaints/<int:id>/status', methods=['PUT'])
def update_status(id):
    data = request.json
    complaint = Complaint.query.get(id)
    if complaint:
        complaint.status = data['status']
        db.session.commit()
        return jsonify({"message": "Status updated successfully."})
    else:
        return jsonify({"error": "Complaint not found"}), 404

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)

from PIL import Image
import tensorflow as tf
import numpy as np

Then, add this function above your /api/complaints route:

python
def classify_image(image_path):
    # load image
    img = Image.open(image_path).resize((224, 224))
    img_array = np.array(img) / 255.0
    img_array = np.expand_dims(img_array, axis=0)

    # for now, hard-coded dummy logic:
    # you can replace with a trained model.predict() later
    # we'll pretend if image is very dark, it's a pothole
    avg_pixel = np.mean(img_array)
    if avg_pixel < 0.5:
        return "pothole"
    else:
        return "garbage"

💡 Step 3: Modify your submit route

Replace:

python
category = 'unknown'

with

python
category = classify_image(os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename))

So your full submit route becomes:

python
@app.route('/api/complaints', methods=['POST'])
def submit_complaint():
    description = request.form['description']
    latitude = request.form['latitude']
    longitude = request.form['longitude']
    image = request.files['image']
    image_path = os.path.join(app.config['UPLOAD_FOLDER'], image.filename)
    image.save(image_path)

    # generate Google Maps link
    maps_url = f"https://maps.google.com/?q={latitude},{longitude}"

    # AI category detection
    category = classify_image(image_path)

    complaint = Complaint(
        description=description,
        image_filename=image.filename,
        latitude=float(latitude),
        longitude=float(longitude),
        maps_url=maps_url,
        category=category
    )
    db.session.add(complaint)
    db.session.commit()
    return jsonify({"message": "Complaint submitted successfully."})

✅ Result:

  • You upload the photo

  • The code classifies it as “pothole” or “garbage” based on brightness

  • Stores the category in the database
